{
  "id": "barbarossa",
  "title": "Operation Barbarossa",
  "theater": "eastern-front",
  "dates": {
    "start": "1941-06-22",
    "end": "1941-12-05"
  },
  "summary": "The largest military operation in history, Operation Barbarossa was the German invasion of the Soviet Union, opening the Eastern Front of the Second World War. Three million German and Axis troops advanced on a front stretching 2,900 km, achieving stunning initial victories before being halted before Moscow.",
  "background": "Despite the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, Hitler had always viewed the Soviet Union as the ideological and racial enemy he intended to destroy. Planning began in December 1940 with Directive 21. The operation aimed to destroy Soviet forces west of the Dvina–Dnieper rivers before autumn.",
  "context": "Barbarossa was more than a military campaign: it was a racial and ideological war of annihilation. The Commissar Order mandated the execution of captured Soviet political officers. The Einsatzgruppen — SS mobile killing units — followed the army and began the mass murder of Jews, communist officials, and others. Army Group Centre's encirclement battles at Białystok, Minsk, Smolensk, and Vyazma-Bryansk produced the largest prisoner hauls in military history, yet Soviet resistance did not collapse as Hitler had anticipated. The six-week delay caused by the Balkans campaign (April–May 1941) meant Barbarossa began too late to avoid the Russian winter — a delay that may have cost Germany Moscow and the war.",
  "combatants": {
    "axis": {
      "commanders": [
        "Gerd von Rundstedt",
        "Fedor von Bock",
        "Wilhelm Ritter von Leeb"
      ],
      "strength": "3,000,000 troops, 3,580 tanks, 7,184 artillery pieces",
